{{wiktionary|Grievance}}
{{other}}
{{About||the arguments in political science theory|greed versus grievance|issues related to labour disputes|Grievance (labour)}}

In general, '''grievance''' (from class. lat. ''gravis'': heavy) is a [[wrong]] or [[wikt:hardship|hardship]] suffered, real or supposed, which forms legitimate grounds of [[complaint]]. In the past, the word meant [[Oppression|oppressive]] state of things.<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]</ref>

==History and politics==
{{multiple issues|
{{Unreferenced|section|date=December 2006}}
{{Globalize|date=December 2010}}
}}

The revolt of English barons in the early thirteenth century which led to the [[Magna Carta]] of 1215 was partly motivated by grievances against abuses by [[John of England|King John]]. This right to [[Petition]] the king, for grievances, was affirmed in the [[Bill of Rights 1689]]

The [[United States Declaration of Independence]] is mainly an enumeration of the colonists' grievances against [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]].

